    {
      "title": "Angular SHM",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Angular Simple Harmonic Motion&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>A body free to rotate about a given axis can make angular oscillations. For example, a wooden stick nailed to a wall can oscillate about its mean position in the vertical plane.</p><p>The conditions for an angular oscillation to be angular simple harmonic motion are</p><p>(i) when a body is displaced through an angle from the mean position $\\left( \\theta =0;\\tau =0 \\right)$, the resultant torque (acts which) is proportional to the angle displaced,</p><p>(ii) this torque is restoring in nature and it tries to bring the body towards the mean position.</p><p>It the angular displacement of the body at an instant is $\\theta $, then resultant torque on the body,</p><p>$\\tau =-\\text{k}\\theta $ (1)</p><p>If the moment of inertia is $\\text{I}$, the angular acceleration is</p><p>$\\alpha =\\frac{\\tau }{\\text{I}}=-\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{I}}\\theta $</p><p>or,</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\theta }{\\text{d}{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}=-{{\\omega }^{2}}\\theta ;\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ where }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\omega =\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{I}}}$ (2)</p><p>Solution of equation (2) is,</p><p>$\\theta ={{\\theta }_{0}}\\text{sin}\\left( \\omega t+\\phi \\right)$ (3)</p><p>where ${{\\theta }_{0}}$ is the maximum angular displacement on either side.</p><p>Angular velocity at time ' $\\text{t}$ ' is given by</p><p>$\\omega =\\frac{\\text{d}\\theta }{\\text{dt}}={{\\theta }_{0}}\\omega \\text{cos}\\left( \\omega \\text{t}+\\phi \\right)$ (4)</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db9ac03b9dcaf1afe29a"
    },
    {
      "title": "Simple Pendulum",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Simple Pendulum</strong></h3><p>A point mass suspended by a massless inextensible string from a rigid support constitutes a simple pendulum. In reality neither point mass nor massless string exist. So we can never construct a simple pendulum strictly according to its definition. A small heavy spherical mass suspended from a light inextensible string constitutes an approximate simple pendulum.</p><p>Now when the pendulum is pulled to one side and released, it will swing to and fro describing an arc of a circle in a vertical plane (as the string is inextensible), i.e., the displacement involved in the motion is angular. So the motion of a simple pendulum is angular and oscillatory. Here restoring torque about $\\text{S}$ is developed due to the weight of the pendulum as shown in Fig., i.e.,</p><p>$\\tau =-\\text{mg}\\times \\text{CE}=-\\text{mgLsin}\\theta $</p><p>[negative sign is used as direction of torque is opposite to displacement].</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"198\" height=\"179\"></p><p>If $\\theta $ is small $\\text{sin}\\theta =\\theta $, so</p><p>$\\tau =-\\text{mgL}\\theta $ (1)</p><p>i.e., restoring torque is linear, so motion will be angular simple harmonic,</p><p>Now as in case of rotational motion :</p><p>$\\tau =\\text{I}\\alpha =\\text{m}{{\\text{L}}^{2}}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\theta }{\\text{d}{{\\text{t}}^{2}}} \\right)\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left[ \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ as }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ I}=\\text{m}{{\\text{L}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\alpha =\\frac{{{\\text{d}}^{2}}\\theta }{\\text{d}{{\\text{t}}^{2}}} \\right]$ (2)</p><p>So from Eqns. (1) and (2),</p><p>$\\mathrm{mL}^2 \\frac{\\mathrm{d}^2 \\theta}{\\mathrm{dt}^2}=-\\mathrm{mgL} \\theta$</p><p>$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}^2 \\mathrm{q}}{\\mathrm{dt}^2}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{g}}{\\mathrm{L}} \\theta$</p><p>$\\frac{\\mathrm{d}^2 \\theta}{\\mathrm{dt}^2}=-\\omega^2 \\theta$ with $\\omega^2=\\frac{\\mathrm{g}}{\\mathrm{L}}$ (3)</p><p>Eqn. (3) is the standard equation of angular simple harmonic motion with time period $\\text{T}=\\left( 2\\pi /\\omega \\right)$; so here</p><p>${{\\text{T}}_{0}}=2\\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{L}}{\\text{g}}}$ (4)</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db9ac03b9dcaf1afe29b"
    },
    {
      "title": "Effects on Simple Pendulum",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Effects on Simple Pendulum</strong></h3><p>(1) If $\\theta $ is not small, $\\text{sin}\\theta \\ne \\theta $. the motion will be oscillatory but not simple harmonic.</p><p>(2) Also here tension $\\ne \\text{mgcos}\\theta $ but tension $\\left( -\\text{mgcos}\\theta \\right)=\\left( \\text{m}{{\\text{v}}^{2}}/\\text{L} \\right)$ as the mass $\\text{m}$ moves in the arc of a circle of radius $\\text{L}$.</p><p>(3) If a simple pendulum is in a carriage which is accelerating with acceleration $\\vec{a}$, then</p><p>${{\\vec{g}}_{\\text{eff}}}=\\vec{g}-\\vec{a}$</p><p>e.g., if the acceleration $\\vec{a}$ is upwards, then</p><p>\\(\\left|\\vec{g}_{\\text {eff }}\\right|=\\mathrm{g}+\\text { a and T }=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{l}}{\\mathrm{g}+\\mathrm{a}}}\\)<br>If the acceleration \\(\\vec{a}\\) is downwards, then ( \\(\\mathrm{g}&gt;\\mathrm{a})\\)<br>\\(\\left|\\vec{g}_{\\text {eff }}\\right|=\\mathrm{g}-\\text { a and T }=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{l}}{\\mathrm{g}-\\mathrm{a}}}\\)</p><p>It the acceleration $\\vec{a}$ is in horizontal direction, then</p><p>$\\left| {{{\\vec{g}}}_{\\text{eff}}} \\right|=\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{g}}^{2}}}$</p><p>In a freely falling lift ${{\\text{g}}_{\\text{eff }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}=0$ and $\\text{T}=\\infty $, i.e., the pendulum will not oscillate.</p><p>(4) If in addition to gravity one additional force $\\vec{F}$, (e.g., electrostatic force ${{\\vec{F}}_{e}}$ ) is also acting on the bob, then in that case,</p><p>${{\\vec{g}}_{\\text{eff}}}=\\vec{g}+\\frac{{\\vec{F}}}{\\text{m}}$</p><p>Here, $\\text{m}$ is the mass of the bob.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db9ac03b9dcaf1afe29c"
    }
  ],
